  "meta": {
    "title": "RISE Score",
    "doi": "10.1212/WNL.0000000000209221",
    "cff_info": "<!-- Hidden Information for RISE Score -->\n<div id=\"fieldInfoRISE\" style=\"display: none; margin-top: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 10px; border-radius: 5px;\">\n  <h4>RISE Score</h4>\n  <p><i>Campos-Fernandez et al., 2024</i></p>\n  <p><b>DOI:</b> <a href=\"https://doi.org/10.1212/WNL.0000000000209221\" target=\"_blank\">10.1212/WNL.0000000000209221</a></p>\n\n  <h4>Factors and Points</h4>\n  <ul>\n    <li><b>Premorbid mRS:</b> \n      <ul>\n        <li>mRS ≥2: 1 point</li>\n      </ul>\n    </li>\n    <li><b>VASOGRADE:</b>\n      <ul>\n        <li>Yellow: 1 point</li>\n        <li>Red: 2 points</li>\n      </ul>\n    </li>\n    <li><b>Surgical Treatment:</b> \n      <ul>\n        <li>Yes: 1 point</li>\n      </ul>\n    </li>\n    <li><b>Seizures:</b>\n      <ul>\n        <li>Early-onset seizures: 1 point</li>\n      </ul>\n    </li>\n  </ul>\n\n  <h4>Risk by RISE Score</h4>\n  <p>After 5 years:</p>\n  <ul>\n    <li>0-1 points: <b>2.9%</b> risk</li>\n    <li>2-3 points: <b>20.8%</b> risk</li>\n    <li>4-5 points: <b>75.7%</b> risk</li>\n  </ul>\n\n  <h4>Clinical Utility</h4>\n  <p>\n    The RISE score is a practical tool for predicting the risk of late seizures following subarachnoid hemorrhage (SAH). It provides clear guidance for clinical decisions regarding follow-up and preventive strategies.\n  </p>\n\n  <h4>Additional Study Information</h4>\n  <table style=\"width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin-top: 10px;\">\n    <thead>\n      <tr style=\"background-color: #f2f2f2;\">\n        <th style=\"border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px;\">Category</th>\n        <th style=\"border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px;\">Details</th>\n      </tr>\n    </thead>\n    <tbody>\n      <tr>\n        <td style=\"border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px;\"><b>Score Name</b></td>\n        <td style=\"border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px;\">RISE Score</td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td style=\"border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px;\"><b>Population</b></td>\n        <td style=\"border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px;\">\n          Derivation: 419 patients, Vall d’Hebron University Hospital (2012-2021)<br>\n          Validation: 308 patients, Bellvitge University Hospital (2011-2022)\n        </td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td style=\"border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px;\"><b>Statistical Methods</b></td>\n        <td style=\"border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px;\">Multiple Cox regression model</td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td style=\"border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px;\"><b>Validation Methods</b></td>\n        <td style=\"border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px;\">\n          Internal: Retrospective cohort (Vall d’Hebron University Hospital)<br>\n          External: Retrospective cohort (Bellvitge University Hospital)\n        </td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td style=\"border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px;\"><b>Performance Metrics</b></td>\n        <td style=\"border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px;\">\n          AUC: 0.82 (derivation), 0.82 (validation)<br>\n          Risk scores: 2.9% (0-1 points), 20.8% (2-3 points), 75.7% (4-5 points)\n        </td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td style=\"border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px;\"><b>Generalizability</b></td>\n        <td style=\"border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px;\">\n          High (validated in a separate cohort)\n        </td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td style=\"border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px;\"><b>Clinical Utility</b></td>\n        <td style=\"border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px;\">\n          Useful for personalized treatment and follow-up after SAH.\n        </td>\n      </tr>\n    </tbody>\n  </table>\n</div>\n",
    "authors": "Campos-Fernández D, Rodrigo-Gisbert M, Abraira L, et al.",
    "journal": "Neurology",
    "year": 2024,
    "clinical_utility": "The RISE score is a practical tool for predicting the risk of late seizures following subarachnoid hemorrhage (SAH). It provides clear guidance for clinical decisions regarding follow-up and preventive strategies.",
    "outcome": "Predictive Model for Estimating the Risk of Epilepsy After Aneurysmal Subarachnoid Hemorrhage"
  },
  "thresholds": {
    "group1": 20.0,
    "group2": 2.0
  },
  "predictors": [
    {
      "name": "Premorbid mRS",
      "options": [
        {
          "label": "<2",
          "points": 0
        },
        {
          "label": "≥2",
          "points": 1
        }
      ],
      "assess": "The mRS assesses functional independence before the onset of the aneurysmal subarachnoid hemorrhage (aSAH). A score ≥2 indicates moderate to severe disability. Higher premorbid mRS is associated with an increased risk of post-aSAH epilepsy."
    },
    {
      "name": "VASOGRADE",
      "options": [
        {
          "label": "Green",
          "points": 0
        },
        {
          "label": "Yellow",
          "points": 1
        },
        {
          "label": "Red",
          "points": 2
        }
      ],
      "assess": "Combines two clinical scales (WFNS and modified Fisher scale) to evaluate the severity of aSAH and stratifies patients into Green (low risk), Yellow (moderate risk), and Red (high risk) categories. A Red VASOGRADE score doubles the epilepsy risk compared to Yellow."
    },
    {
      "name": "Surgical Treatment",
      "options": [
        {
          "label": "No",
          "points": 0
        },
        {
          "label": "Yes",
          "points": 1
        }
      ],
      "assess": "Surgical management (e.g., clipping of aneurysms) versus endovascular coiling or conservative treatment. Surgical intervention is linked to a higher epilepsy risk compared to non-surgical approaches."
    },
    {
      "name": "Acute Symptomatic Seizures / Early Seizures",
      "options": [
        {
          "label": "No",
          "points": 0
        },
        {
          "label": "Yes",
          "points": 1
        }
      ],
      "assess": "Seizures occurring within the first seven days of the aSAH event. Acute symptomatic seizures doubles the likelihood of developing epilepsy."
    }
  ],
